FT  23 AUG 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There is a hearties/aesthetes split this evening which will be irritating
for some. Apart from EastEnders and the news, BBC1 is devoted entirely to
the Commonwealth Games starting at 7.00 and continuing until 1.30 in the
morning. Scheduled events include the men's and women's 100 metres, with
Linford Christie looking for yet another victory, the men's and women's 3000
metres, men's and women's 400 metres, and the men's 110 metres hurdles which
will presumably be won by Colin Jackson. Channel 4, however, offers an
interesting competitive attraction. After Episode 2 in their repeat of
Lipstick On Your Collar (10.00) which was not the best series ever created
by the late Dennis Potter, they offer the first full length showing on
television of Potter's 1993 Edinburgh Festival lecture (11.10). This was the
occasion when he attacked the BBC's top men, Duke Hussey and John Birt, whom
he called 'croak-voiced Daleks', and Rupert Murdoch whose very name stuck in
his throat. On the occasion of the 90th birthday of China's aged leader Deng
Xiaoping Julian O'Halloran provides a profile on BBC2 (9.30).
