<HEADLINE>
FT  23 AUG 94 / BR runs 45% of strike-hit service
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Rail said it ran 45 per cent of its normal services yesterday
afternoon, the largest number of trains to run during strike action since
the start of the railway signal workers' dispute 11 weeks ago.
Railtrack said it had managed to open 40 per cent of the 10,000-mile rail
network to train services, slightly more than during last week's two-day
strike.
The company, which manages British Rail's track, signalling and stations,
said 530 signal workers had worked last week, including 309 members of the
RMT transport union. At the start of the strike only 337 signal workers had
reported for duty including 131 RMT members.
Railtrack yesterday said that it did not yet know how many signal workers
would be working during the present 24-hour stoppage, which ends at midday
today, but it expected a further small increase. BR is seeking to put some
of its staff in Railtrack signal boxes but has not yet done so.
The union denied that there had been any significant return to work by its
members and said they were still 'solidly supporting' the stoppages. It
accused Railtrack of becoming more ruthless in its attempt to open up more
track and break the strike.
The most significant addition to the operating rail network yesterday was
the east coast main line from London to Edinburgh which was open along its
entire length for the first time, BR said.
InterCity ran an almost full service in some regions. The Chiltern line
between London Marylebone, Banbury and Birmingham also ran a nearly normal
service while 90 per cent of trains ran in the Thames region and 60 per cent
on Merseyrail.
Mr Jimmy Knapp, RMT general secretary, said: 'Railtrack have been able to
open up some additional parts of the network today because they have become
more clever, as well as more ruthless, in their exploitation of supervisors,
not through a return to work by RMT signalling grades. If cracks are
developing in the dispute it is on the management side.'
Many of the train operating units of BR have produced detailed timetables of
their services for travellers during the present 24-hour strike.
RMT is planning a further 48-hour strike by signal workers on Tuesday and
Wednesday next week.
</TEXT>
