<HEADLINE>
FT  23 AUG 94 / Safety body holds 21 foreign ships
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A total of 21 foreign ships were detained in UK ports in July after failing
safety inspections, the Marine Safety Agency said yesterday.
The figure comes in the second monthly report on defective vessels arriving
at British ports. The first survey, in June, led to the detention of 17
vessels, three of which were still being held last month.
The government began inspecting foreign ships in UK ports in June after an
inquiry headed by Lord Donaldson into marine pollution incidents produced a
report which heavily criticised marine safety standards.
Mr Robin Bradley, chief executive of the agency which was set up April,
said: 'The response from the shipping industry to our June detention list
has been encouraging. The publication of a monthly list will strengthen our
campaign against unsafe ships.'
Ten of the vessels detained in July had significant defects in their
life-saving and fire-fighting equipment, while six had defects in their
radio installations. Two were held because of shortcomings in their crews,
while one was held because it had serious structural problems.
Five of the ships were registered under the Maltese flag, three were
registered in Liberia and two in Cyprus. Four had been inspected and
approved by the American Bureau of Shipping, three by Bureau Veritas, a
French classification society; and two each by the Norwegian body Det Norkse
Veritas, Germanischer Lloyd, and the Japanese Nippon Kaiji Kyokai. Of the
remaining vessels, two had not been approved at all.
One ship, the United Trust, a Greek-owned general cargo vessel flying the
Maltese flag, had badly corroded bulkheads, decks and support struts. The
chief officer had no papers and the radio receiver did not work. The ship
made temporary repairs and was then allowed to sail to Germany for permanent
repairs.
The failure of some countries that register vessels under their flags to
impose adequate controls has led to a shift towards inspections in the ports
where vessels call.
</TEXT>
