<HEADLINE>
FT  23 AUG 94 / Mexican Elections: A new chance to break with the old ways -
A look at the Mexican election victor's scope to curb the ruling party's
powerful role
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
After his comfortable victory in the Mexican presidential election on
Sunday, Mr Ernesto Zedillo now faces the daunting task of preparing in
little more than three months for a presidency that stretches from December
1 until the end of the year 2000. Officials close to Mr Zedillo indicate
that he will concentrate on three broad areas until December - improving
relations with the opposition and broadening his support in the country,
beginning the reform of the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party, and
establishing policies and picking ministers for the next administration.
None of the three will be easy. Mr Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the leader of the
leftist opposition, yesterday denounced the election as fraudulent, and
promised to challenge the results. Previous attempts to reform the PRI have
all failed, with the party apparently more resistant to change than any
other institution in Mexico. Also, many reforms Mr Zedillo has pledged touch
some of the most powerful and vested interests in the country.
But he will have some advantages. The election results reveal a depth of
support for the PRI even in a highly adverse political year for the party,
and indicate broad if not enthusiastic endorsement for the way the country
has been managed by President Carlos Salinas over the past six years.
With reports of electoral irregularities so far limited, Mr Zedillo can
claim a democratic mandate for his policies. The immediate issue is to heal
the wounds that the long and often bitter campaign generated.
Mr Cardenas of the leftist opposition and Mr Diego Fernandez de Cevallos of
the centre-right opposition both sharply criticised the manner of Mr
Zedillo's victory. They claim that the seemingly unlimited spending of the
ruling party, the biased media coverage of the campaign, and support from
the government indicate an unwillingness PRI to embrace democracy.
Mr Cardenas is his most immediate threat, although his poor showing in the
poll and perception that irregularities were isolated, may weaken his
ability to protest. Yesterday, Mr Cardenas said the fraudulent election was
a grave threat to Mexico's political stability. He called for supporters to
oppose the results. He was joined by an estimated 20,000 supporters, far
fewer than the number that backed him after the 1988 presidential election.
However even Mr Fernandez - whose party has generally supported the PRI -
withheld a full endorsement of Mr Zedillo's victory yesterday morning,
attacking what he called a 'profoundly iniquitous and profoundly unjust'
political system. But he said he would not join the protests, and would
challenge irregularities in the election courts.
Mr Zedillo, in his victory speech, made conciliatory gestures. He asked his
opponents to 'emphasise what we have in common, without sacrificing
differences'. He told foreign correspondents late on Sunday that 'my
responsibility is not only for those who voted for the PRI but those who
voted for other parties. Today, Mexico has a great opportunity to have an
important agreement among all the political parties.'
It is unclear what such an agreement might entail. Many people are so
sceptical about the PRI that they will not believe Mr Zedillo until he makes
specific concessions to the opposition. Mr Enrique Krauze, a prominent
historian, said Mr Zedillo 'should interpret the election as a mandate to
change the system from within.' But, given his way of campaigning and
previous record in government, 'we have not had the slightest sign that
makes us think he is willing to do this.'
Mr Zedillo may choose some members of the opposition to join his cabinet as
a way of winning their support. A plural cabinet would certainly fit in with
his pledge to represent all of Mexico, and not just the PRI. But it remains
to be seen what if any positions Mr Zedillo offers - more importantly the
opposition response is also awaited.
His pledge to reform the PRI will almost certainly form part of his attempts
to forge relations with the opposition.
Mr Zedillo promised in the campaign to separate the PRI from the government,
not to interfere in the ruling party when in office, and to propose
democratic methods for the party to pick its candidates.
Over the next three months, Mr Zedillo and his associates are likely to set
out the broad outlines of internal party reforms rather than making final
decisions, according to Mr Jesus Reyes Heroles, a respected economist who,
as the new head of the PRI's commission of ideology, is expected to play a
key role in drawing up the new policies. He said the reforms would have to
be discussed extensively with the rank-and-file, and agreed by them before
being implemented.
Other Zedillo associates accept the difficulty of pushing through such
reforms, which have always failed in the past. President Carlos Salinas
briefly experimented with internal primaries for some offices, before
abandoning the effort after they had caused bitter divisions in the party.
They seemed mainly to benefit the party old guard, who are generally well
organised to get out the vote.
Giving up the power of patronage would seriously weaken Mr Zedillo, who
would be giving up the traditional mechanism through which the Mexican
president keeps control of party officials and ensures their unwavering
loyalty. For this reason some are doubtful that Mr Zedillo will carry
through on the reforms, and others are worried that if does, he will find it
more difficult to govern the country.
Mr Zedillo's policies in government are likely to reduce his presidential
powers still further. According to officials, his administration will begin
by implementing reforms of the police, and of the judicial system, to make
them both more professional and the judiciary more independent of the
executive, and introduce policies that will devolve more powers to state and
municipal governments.
On the economy Mr Zedillo will work hard to ensure a smooth transition with
the current government. Aides say they will try to reach agreement with the
current administration on public spending priorities for next year. Mr
Zedillo has promised a rise in public investment of 25 per cent for next
year, in an effort to enhance economic growth.
</TEXT>
