<HEADLINE>
FT  23 AUG 94 / Markets welcome budget plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Swedish krona stiffened yesterday and long-term interest rates eased as
financial markets gave an initial welcome to a pledge by the opposition
Social Democratic Party to take tough action to curb fast-growing government
debt if its wins next month's general election. The markets expect the
Social Democrats, the country's biggest political party, to win the election
and had driven up interest rates and speculated against the krona in the
absence of a detailed opposition plan to stem the SKr200bn (Pounds 16.7bn)
budget deficit. The proposal unveiled on Friday evening to strengthen the
budget by SKr61bn over the next four years through a mix of tax rises and
spending cuts has been criticised as 'too little, too late' by the
centre-right government.
</TEXT>
