<HEADLINE>
FT  23 AUG 94 / Dairy trade to challenge new system for milk supply
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain's dairy trade is to challenge the government in court over its
handling of the deregulation of the milk market, warning that retail prices
could be forced up and thousands of jobs lost.
The Dairy Trade Federation, which represents milk processors, said it was
seeking a High Court judicial review because the government had allowed the
creation of 'a monopoly supplier of milk without proper regulation or
control'.
The government gave the go-ahead to the Milk Marketing Board in June to set
up a voluntary dairy farmers' co-operative, Milk Marque, to succeed it when
the market is liberalised on November 1.
Milk Marque has already signed up farmers supplying 65 per cent of milk in
England and Wales and the dairy trade says this control over the market is
allowing it to raise prices by up to 25 per cent under its auction-based
selling system in preparation for the new regime. The federation said the
price rises would cost dairy companies collectively some Pounds 250m a year,
more than the industry's entire current annual profits.
'Consumers could see the prices of some dairy products rising by as much as
18 per cent, adding nearly 0.2 per cent to the retail price index,' said Mr
Jim McMichael-Phillips, federation president.
Simultaneously, the two biggest dairy companies, Northern Foods and Unigate,
warned their operating profits would be hit by the increase in costs,
leading to job losses and a 2p increase in the price of a pint of milk.
Mr William Waldegrave, the agriculture minister, said he would meet both
sides in the dispute on Thursday. He did not rule out referring the new
arrangements to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission, as the dairy trade is
demanding.
However, he said it was hard to tell if the present difficulties were 'more
than the inevitable transitional strains, or whether they represent the
misuse of marketing power by Milk Marque'. The federation, representing an
industry with annual retail sales of Pounds 7bn and a workforce of 70,000,
plans to seek leave for judicial review within the next two weeks. If it is
granted, it hopes the hearing would take place by early October.
The move brings fresh uncertainty to the timing of deregulation, which was
scheduled for April 1. Concern last year from the European Commission and
the dairy trade over the potential monopoly position of Milk Marque forced
the Milk Marketing Board to amend its plans.
Mr Andrew Dare, chief executive of Milk Marque, yesterday accused the dairy
companies of exaggerating the increases and said the largest rise  - for
cheese manufacturers - was about 12 per cent. 'The prices we've arrived at
have not been determined by us but by the bidding behaviour of the
customers,' he added. 'They've indicated they're prepared to pay that
amount.'
Lex, Page 16
Dairy industry locks horns with new market, Page 9
London stocks, Page 34
</TEXT>
