<HEADLINE>
FT  22 AUG 94 / This Week: Grade's week - Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALKARIM JIVANI, television editor of Time Out
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Vitali Vitaliev, Russia's answer to Clive James, returns to the Ukraine five
years after he defected in Travels With My Camera (Monday, 9.00-10.00, C4),
a series that aims to do away with the paraphernalia of programme-making by
arming the presenter with a Hi-8 camera to get an immediacy absent from
other programmes. But Vitaliev's technological illiteracy made this
difficult - he jokes that the documentary should be renamed 'Troubles With
My Camera'. In the five years he has been away the economy has been turned
upside down. Hyperinflation means an apple costs a pensioner a quarter of
her monthly income, a shortage of small change means that phone boxes are
free and the most powerful people are gangster-like 'businessmen'.
At the other end of the Asian land mass there are daily rumours that Deng
Xiao Ping, China's nonagenerian leader is dead. To mark his birthday on
Monday the BBC has produced a profile The People's Dictator (Tuesday,
9.30-10.20, BBC2). In the last few months, Deng has disappeared from public
view but his presence still looms large. Reporter Julian O'Halloran, who
covered the Tianamen Square demonstrations, gives an absorbing account of
how Deng has kept a grip on the greasy pole since 1916 by being a supremely
pragmatic politician who even managed to reinstate himself after being
denounced during the Cultural Revolution. But he is no diplomat - his
remarks to Mrs Thatcher are said to have been so rude that the interpreter
thought it best not to translate them. And he's certainly not a democrat -
China is still waiting for the political reforms that were promised
alongside economic liberalisation. The vital question is what will happen
after Deng dies - one that the documentary, unfortunately, ducks.
The early years of TV were dominated by showman entrepreneurs - literally so
in the case of Lew (now Lord) Grade whose first claim to fame was as a
champion Charleston dancer. The BBC is paying tribute to the last of the
old-style media moghuls with a season of programmes starting with ATV Night
(Saturday, 7.55-12.05am) which will be introduced from the foyer of the
Crossroads Motel, famous as the setting for Lord Grade's most successful
early evening soap opera.
Alas Meg Richardson (Noele Gordon) who played the all-controlling
matriarch-cum-motel owner has checked into the celestial chalet now. But her
screen daughter, Jill Richardson (Jane Rossington), will step into the
breach. The line-up includes compilation programmes and episodes from Edward
VII, Danger Man and The Muppet Show. But the centrepiece of the evening is
The Persuader (9.00-9.50) in which Lord Grade is interviewed by his nephew
Michael Grade, chief executive of Channel Four.
Although Lord Grade doesn't quite give us the gen on the reasons for his
departure from ITV, following a boardroom battle with Robert Holmes a Court,
he is generous with the anecdotes which include some gems. If you only watch
one programme this week, watch this.
</TEXT>
