<HEADLINE>
FT  22 AUG 94 / Economic gloom continues to fade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Public opinion about employment prospects and the state of the economy
continues to improve, according to the latest FT/MORI Mood of the Nation
index.
While the nation would appear still to be pessimistic overall, the index has
risen since April, its lowest point this year and only one point off the
lowest level since the index started in April last year. That low point of
79 was reached in October.
The belief that the mood can only get better, at least in the short term,
has led to some changes in the way the index is being presented. While
national pessimism was reflected previously in a rising index, using a 100
base set in April 1993, the graph has now in effect been flipped on its head
so that that the gloom factor is represented by a depreciating figure and
higher spirits by a rising one.
While there is some stirring of optimism, it would be more accurate to say
that people are slightly less pessimistic than they were a year ago.
The results of the survey show that nearly one in three managers and
executives are concerned about losing their jobs in the next 12 months, a
marginally smaller ratio than a month ago.
The changes in attitudes remain quite subtle and a further analysis of
managerial anxiety shows merely that the depth of concern among some is not
quite what it was.
Concerns deepen when the 35-to-44 age range is considered. Some 40 per cent
of people in this grouping are worried about losing their jobs.
Professor Robert Worcester, chairman of MORI Financial Services, the index
compiler, said: 'What these findings reflect most of all is a middle-class,
middle-aged malaise.'
Some 26 per cent of this class think the economy is going to deteriorate and
only 35 per cent of them think it will get better.
However, pessimism remains even deeper among manual workers. Only 20 per
cent of them can see any prospect of improvement. Prof Worcester said:
'While things appear bleak to the middle classes, they still look worse to
the working class.'
</TEXT>
