<HEADLINE>
FT  22 AUG 94 / Bonuses seen as route to end yearly pay rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Increasing use of bonus schemes is paving the way for an end to the annual
pay rise, a report suggests today.
The report by the Confederation of British Industry and Wyatt, the human
resource and actuarial consultancy, says that employers are broadening their
use of incentive and profit-related pay schemes.
The adoption of such variable pay systems partly reflects a desire by
employers to use them as a lever to break away from or reduce the annual
rise in basic pay to which many remain committed.
The growing popularity and sophistication of the schemes is arousing
suspicion among some employees since they involve unconsolidated pay. For
the same reason they are attractive to employers who want greater
flexibility in their pay arrangements and want to reduce their pay bills if
business deteriorates.
Mr Oliver Overstall, Wyatt's UK director of compensation strategy, said: 'It
is almost incredible that with record low inflation rates, many UK
organisations still ratchet up their fixed pay costs by incremental
additions to base pay.'
The survey, which analysed 300 schemes in 100 companies, defines variable
pay, widely adopted in the US, as the 'at risk' part of a wage packet,
covering individual bonuses, team incentives, gain-sharing, share schemes,
profit-sharing and spot awards - one-off payments for a job well done.
The most generous types of variable pay, it says, are restricted share
schemes and key-contributor schemes, usually confined to senior management.
These can sometimes be worth up to 100 per cent of basic salary.
The survey says that performance measures vary between different classes of
staff. Profitability, revenue or income generation are most common among
middle and senior management. Quality and speed are often used for clerical
and supervisory staff. Production volume and quality measures tend to be
adopted for manual workers.
Companies are using different systems for different purposes, says the
report, which says variable pay is not replacing performance-related pay but
often complements it.
Profit-related pay schemes approved by the Inland Revenue are gaining in
popularity. Nearly one in 10 private-sector employees are covered by such
schemes which give tax relief on an amount of pay linked to profit.
One-sixth of those surveyed said they planned to introduce or extend a
profit-sharing scheme in the next two years.
Mr Overstall said: 'If UK employers want to maintain the competitive edge
they have fought so painfully to achieve, it seems evident that they should,
as quickly as possible, move the bulk of any pay increases into the truly
variable element of their compensation framework.'
This would give them a more flexible pay platform, he argued, and added:
'The demise of the universally held notion of the annual pay rise could then
be on the cards in the UK.'
Variable Pay Systems. CBI publication sales, Centre Point, 103 New Oxford
Street, London WC1A 1DU. Pounds 20 for non-members, Pounds 10 for members.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
