<HEADLINE>
FT  22 AUG 94 / Insurer to speed training reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sun Alliance is to speed up plans to merge the training of its life
insurance direct sales force and that of 'tied agents' - financial advisers
who sell its products - after recommendations from regulators.
The insurer, one of the UK's largest, received a report from Lautro, the
life industry watchdog, this month and told its agents just over a week ago
that the training merger would be brought forward.
Mr Mike Austen, managing director of Sun Alliance's life and pensions
operation, emphasised that Lautro's report had not found any area where the
competence of any sales agent was in doubt and had not identified any issues
relating to investor protection.
The changes being made are similar to those being carried out in other life
companies.
After visits from Lautro, both Norwich Union and Nationwide building society
took the more drastic course of suspending their financial services sales
forces temporarily for retraining. Both later decided to reduce sharply the
number of authorised agents.
The size of Sun Alliance's life and pensions sales force, including tied
agents, has dropped by almost a third from 1,700 in June 1993.
