<HEADLINE>
FT  22 AUG 94 / Check-off wins companies' support
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The check-off system for paying union subscriptions directly from pay
packets helps in 'promoting good industrial relations', say 53 per cent of
companies in an Institute of Manpower Studies study.
Only 5 per cent see the strengthening of trade union organisation in their
company as a disadvantage, while the costs of its administration are not
seen as a problem.
The survey, published today, shows that the legislation introduced last year
requiring trade unions to seek approval from their members every three years
for check-off will have only a 'modest' impact on existing arrangements.
Only six cases were found of companies withdrawing from check-off and none
were due to the rule changes.
Check-off is seen as important by companies for efficiency and co-operation
in industrial relations.
A number of trade unions believe they have secured new members as a result
of the legislation and their subsequent campaigns to secure membership
approval, although others are concerned that they will lose members.
After September 1 a union member will be able to take legal action against
their employer if the subscription continues to be paid without their
approval.
Both the GMB general union and the MSF technical union are claiming new
members and a net gain in their total membership, although many unions have
expressed concern that they will suffer a net membership loss.
</TEXT>
