<HEADLINE>
FT  22 AUG 94 / Lib Dems tax shake-up proposes top rate of 60%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Liberal Democrats are poised to announce a radical package of tax and
benefit measures which would take more than 50,000 people out of taxation
and impose a top tax rate of 60 per cent on incomes over Pounds 100,000.
Mr Alan Beith, the party's deputy leader, will announce the proposals this
week in a paper expected to become policy at the party conference next
month.
The paper proposes the introduction of three higher rates of income tax at
unspecified levels, together with the integration of the tax system with the
national insurance and benefits systems.
Liberal Democrat officials said no decisions had been taken on the structure
of the higher tax rates, or the thresholds at which they would take effect.
However the paper guarantees a top level of no more than 60 per cent.
The paper suggests that a number of existing tax reliefs valued by
middle-income taxpayers should be abolished, including mortgage interest tax
relief and the married couples allowance.
It proposes a transfer of resources to finance a range of extra benefits
designed to have the greatest impact on those with lower income.
The proposed benefits include an increase in child support of Pounds 5 per
family and the removal from the tax net of 50,000 low-paid workers by
equalising the threshold for income tax and national insurance payments.
Party officials said the system was intended to increase the fairness of the
tax system by improving benefits for the lower paid and making income tax
payments more progressive than has been the rule under the Conservatives.
Tough controls intended to maintain the quality of television and radio
broadcasting will be proposed today by Mr Robert Maclennan, Liberal Democrat
media spokesman.
The proposals would remove regulatory supervision of broadcasting from the
government. Regulation of the BBC, ITV and independent radio would be
transferred to an Office of Broadcasting.
</TEXT>
