<HEADLINE>
FT  22 AUG 94 / Economists find worrying fall on the supply side
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Economists have found fresh cause for concern about the health of the UK
economy - a reduction in the supply of economists.
British schools are apparently producing instead a generation of would-be
entrepreneurs who see business studies as a route to fulfilment.
Mr Paul Walton, economist with James Capel, the UK securities house, says in
a report that the number of candidates for A-level in economics  - often
termed 'the dismal science' - hit a 20-year low this year at 30,885, a drop
since last year of 15.2 per cent. It peaked at 43,500 in 1983.
While the pass rate has improved to 78.4 per cent (up from 63.7 per cent in
1978), Mr Walton says it has not kept up with other subjects - only social
sciences and computing have worse failure rates.
Charts produced by James Capel show a 'tentative relationship with the
economic cycle', and Mr Walton argues that the result is likely to be 'a
smaller band of more rigorously trained economists'.
The sharp fall in A-level economics has been balanced by a rise in
applicants for business studies, which was introduced as a subject only 15
years ago. Applications for the subject, which concentrates on financial
analysis and management science, rose by 9.9 per cent this year to 24,920.
Mr Walton's analysis for James Capel suggests that the rise of the stock
market, and the 'cult of the businessman', have encouraged this trend. He
adds that pass rates have improved to 80.2 per cent this year, from 49.5 per
cent in 1978. However, the proportion earning the top 'A' grade remains the
lowest for any subject, at 6.6 per cent.
Figures for numbers of full-time undergraduates at UK universities show that
the trend is continuing in higher education. The numbers studying business
and management studies rose by 12.9 per cent this year.
</TEXT>
