<HEADLINE>
FT  22 AUG 94 / University staffing trails student rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Academic staffing levels have failed to keep up with rising numbers of
full-time students in UK universities during the past four years of
expansion, government statistics published today show.
While student numbers at 'old' universities - excluding former colleges and
polytechnics upgraded to university status from 1992 onwards - have risen by
34 per cent over the past four years, the number of full-time academic staff
has risen by only 13 per cent.
The rise in staff numbers was concentrated on research while the number of
teaching staff increased by only 7.6 per cent, said Mr David Triesman,
general secretary of the Association of University Teachers.
Mr Triesman said this meant the average ratio of full-time students to
teaching staff had risen from 10.6:1 to 14:1. He said: 'Treating
professional staff as if they were machines that could be set to run faster
and faster places a low value on quality in higher education, which is
suffering from go-stop planning and gross underfunding.'
There has been a cut of 30 per cent in public funding per student since
1980, says a report produced for the Committee of Vice-chancellors and
Principals, which represents universities, by London university's Institute
of Education.
The report predicts 'continued financial stringency', and said 'no change of
government would alter the broad outlook to any significant extent'.
It suggested that universities' strategic plans should incorporate the
possibility of a period of consolidation, for reasons including 'the
capacity of the labour market to absorb very rapid increases in graduate
numbers' and 'the maintenance of acceptable quality'.
The proportion of students winning first-class honours degrees has risen by
50 per cent in 11 years to 9 per cent, from 6 per cent in 1983.
The statistics also reveal that numbers of mature students have risen
substantially, with 18 per cent of new full-time undergraduates being aged
21 or over - compared with 10 per cent 10 years ago. Part-time students also
showed an increase - of 11 per cent - on the previous year.
Subjects enjoying the largest increases among undergraduate entrants last
year were law, computer studies and psychology, while teacher training and
nursing saw a decline in new recruits.
Expansion has raised the number of women in higher education - they account
for 23 per cent of academic staff (up from 15 per cent 10 years before), and
for 47 per cent of full-time undergraduates (from 42 per cent a decade
earlier).
However, men still outnumber women by six to one on engineering and
technology courses and three to one in mathematical sciences.
University Statistics 1993-94 - Students and Staff. Universities Statistical
Record, PO Box 130, Cheltenham, Glos GL50 3SE. Pounds 17.50. Longer Term
Prospects for British Higher Education. CVCP, 29 Tavistock Square, London
WC1H 9EZ. Pounds 5.
</TEXT>
