<HEADLINE>
FT  22 AUG 94 / Panic as French quit Rwanda
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUKAVU
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
France pulled its last troops out of Rwanda yesterday, triggering chaos at a
border crossing as Hutu refugees tried to storm across into Zaire, Reuter
reports from Bukavu.
After being blocked by Zairean troops firing into the air, the refugees last
night were streaming south along a riverside trail to another border
crossing eight miles away.
The rush to the Ruzizi border post leading into Bukavu broke out less than
half an hour after 150 French Legionnaires crossed into Zaire, signalling an
end to the French humanitarian mission in Rwanda.
Ethiopian United Nations peacekeepers stood by helplessly as hundreds of
refugees swarmed across a rickety bridge and tried to overrun the Zairean
border post.
While the Zairean troops stopped the rush to the border post, other refugees
managed to swim across the river or to get across using straw mats as
makeshift rafts.
The chaotic scenes provided an unwelcome background to the end of France's
controversial two-month humanitarian mission.
Now that the French have left, the Hutus fear reprisals by members of the
Tutsi tribe, who have ousted the former government and seized power in
Rwanda.
The Hutus have voiced suspicions of the 800-strong Ethiopian contingent,
which is part of the 2,200-strong African UN mission in Rwanda. They suspect
the Ethiopians may be sympathetic to the Tutsis.
The French pulled out despite concern by the UN and aid agencies about the
implications for the south-western Rwanda protection zone they had guarded.
French officials say there are 2.5m people in the 'safe zone' against only
1.9m in the rest of Rwanda.
In the last two days more than 45,000 Hutus have managed to cross into
Zaire, joining many thousands of others already there.
Zaire said the border closure at Bukavu was motivated by a fear of a huge
refugee influx like that at Goma recently. Some relief officials also voiced
fears of a new exodus. 'We're trying to prevent them clogging up the town
because it is an absolute death trap,' said one aid worker.
The office of the UN High Commissioner for Refugees said trucks today would
ferry Rwandans split from their families by the abrupt closure back to
Bukavu and funnel others to new camps on the outskirts of the settlement.
</TEXT>
