<HEADLINE>
FT  22 AUG 94 / Moslem refugees pour out of Bihac
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Tens of thousands of refugees yesterday streamed out of Bihac, the Moslem
pocket in north-western Bosnia as UN officials said Bosnian government
troops had overrun it, Laura Silber reports from Belgrade.
Bihac has been the stronghold for nearly a year of a rebel Bosnian Moslem
leader, Mr Fikret Abdic, a communist entrepreneur. The destruction of his
effort to form a personal fiefdom in Bihac will bolster the Bosnian army,
which has used its important 5th Corps and could free up troops to fight
against Bosnian Serb forces elsewhere in Bosnia.
UN refugee officials said as many as 20,000 people had been displaced over
the weekend, according to unconfirmed reports. Panicked civilians were
trying to flee the dense Moslem heartland into Serb-held areas of Croatia.
'Roads are flooded by people.' said Mr Peter Kessler, spokesman for the UN
High Commissioner for Refugees. UN officials yesterday were trying to help
the refugees - some of whom were trapped in a mined no-man's land between
rebels Serb forces and Croatian troops.
Croatia so far has allowed 50 ethnic Croats to cross the border, said a UN
official. Rebel Serbs were chasing the refugees into the minefields, said Mr
Kessler.
Refugees started to leave the Bihac pocket when Mr Abdic's revolt began to
collapse last week. Bosnian army troops gained control of the dense Moslem
heartland early yesterday, reported Sarajevo radio.
</TEXT>
