<HEADLINE>
FT  22 AUG 94 / AT&amp;T acts to fend off telecoms contest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AT&amp;T is campaigning to hold back further competition that could
significantly cut prices in the transatlantic telecommunications market.
The move by the largest US telecoms operator comes a month after AT&amp;T was
granted a draft licence to operate in the UK.
AT&amp;T is urging the Federal Communications Commission, the US telecoms
regulator, not to allow a new form of competition called international
simple resale. Under this system, operators lease international lines and
connect them to the public networks on both sides of the Atlantic.
The resale system is expected to bring cuts in transatlantic call prices at
the expense of established carriers, notably AT&amp;T and British
Telecommunications.
As AT&amp;T pursued its case with the US regulator, telecoms analyst Mr Laurence
Heyworth of Robert Fleming, predicted BT would try to pre-empt resale
competition by making 'massive price cuts on international calls' later this
year.
BT has already been told by Oftel, the UK telecoms regulator, that it must
cut charges by about Pounds 400m before the end of the year.
It had been widely assumed that competition on the transatlantic routes
would open up after the UK's decision last month to grant a draft licence to
AT&amp;T. This followed the US regulatory authorities' approval of BT's Dollars
5.3bn (Pounds 3.4bn) alliance with MCI, the second-largest US operator.
The two companies planning to offer the cheap resale services, MFS and ACC,
already have licences to operate in the UK and are asking the Federal
Communications Commission for permission to offer international simple
resale from the US.
AT&amp;T's argument to the US regulator is that 'while the UK has made progress
over the last year' it is still not as open as the US. This is denied by MFS
and ACC, who have told the commission that Britain offers telecoms resale
operators 'opportunities equivalent to those available under US law'. The
resellers' claims are broadly supported by US regional telecoms companies
with substantial UK interests, which have recently put similar claims to the
US regulator.
Through its MCI alliance, BT wants to become the leading international
operator for multinationals. A loss of international business to new
competitors could hamper its ambition.
Mercury, BT's largest UK competitor, stands to be the main loser from a
transatlantic price war. It earns nearly half its income from international
calls.
A ring that sounds like profit, Page 13
</TEXT>
