<HEADLINE>
FT  20 AUG 94 / Minister faces US threat on Graces
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Getty Museum in Malibu, California, said last night that it had
threatened legal action against the British government in the row over 'The
Three Graces'.
Mr John Walsh, director of the museum, said he had written a 'forceful'
letter to Mr Stephen Dorrell, heritage secretary, complaining about his
refusal to grant an export licence for the sculpture.
Mr Walsh said: 'At every turn in this sorry saga, our efforts to acquire the
statue and to exhibit it to the public have been frustrated by the delays in
and working of the export licence system in this case.'
The National Heritage Department said last night: 'If the matter goes to
court we will defend our position vigorously.'
'The Three Graces' was sold in 1989 after the Victoria and Albert museum in
London said the Pounds 1m price was too high. Since being bought by the
Getty Museum last year the statue has been awaiting an export licence.
The museum is seeking to take the sculpture to California but Mr Dorrell
deferred the application earlier this month.
British museums are battling to raise Pounds 7.6m to keep the statue in this
country, assisted by a pledge of Pounds 1m by Mr John Paul Getty, son of the
museum's founder.
Weekend FT, Page XX
</TEXT>
