<HEADLINE>
FT  20 AUG 94 / Virgin-Delta airline pact blocked by US disapproval
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A planned transatlantic alliance between Virgin Atlantic Airways of the UK
and Delta Air Lines of the US was yesterday effectively shelved following a
decision by the US Department of Transportation to withhold its approval.
The deal was supposed to come into effect on November 1, but Delta and
Virgin said they had postponed implementation indefinitely because the
department was not prepared to act in advance of negotiations on a fresh
aviation treaty between the US and the UK.
Under the existing aviation treaty, only two US airlines - United and
American - are allowed to fly into London Heathrow airport, the world's
largest. The US has been pushing the UK to give all US airlines access to
Heathrow.
The agreement between Delta and Virgin would have given Delta a different
form of access to Heathrow by allowing it to book blocks of 15 to 20 per
cent of the seats on Virgin's flights to London from New York, Newark, Los
Angeles, San Francisco, Miami, Orlando and Boston.
Delta would have independently sold tickets for these seats as though they
were tickets for its own flights, using Delta flight codes. Both airlines
hoped to benefit from the deal through big increases in passenger numbers.
The UK government was in favour of the pact and approved it at the end of
May. The US Justice Department approved it a month later. But the US
Department of Transportation has been unimpressed by UK offers to improve
access to UK regional airports and London Stansted as part of a
liberalisation package, and is demanding bigger concessions.
Delta and Virgin said they still hoped to go ahead with the deal eventually,
and they still planned to implement those parts of it that did not require
government approval. This means the two will share frequent-flyer
programmes, and Virgin will start using Delta's ground facilities at US
airports.
Mr Richard Branson, chairman of Virgin Atlantic, said both airlines were
'deeply disappointed' that the code-sharing agreement had been delayed. He
could not see the logic of approving an earlier code-sharing deal between
USAir and British Airways while delaying a decision over the Virgin/Delta
pact.
