<DATE>940820
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 AUG 94 / Outdoors: The SL, a symphony in heavy metal - Motoring
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STUART MARSHALL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The 50-year-old Dakota, smelling like all old aeroplanes of petrol, oil and
the passage of time, had taken off from Biggin Hill airfield in Kent,
immortalised by the Battle of Britain. Close to an hour later, it rolled to
a standstill on the grass of Swanton Morley.
I jumped out, walked across to an open-topped Mercedes-Benz 320SL, and drove
it away down the kind of track makers use to test cars to destruction.
At 35-40mph (56-64kph), nothing shook, banged or creaked. For all the notice
the Mercedes took of the potholes and bumps, it could have been an average
B-road in Britain.
Why the trip by veteran aircraft to a former second world war bomber base in
East Anglia? First, to make the point that the SL has been around for a very
long time; the type name originated 40 years ago with the 300SL and its
unusual gull-wing doors.
Second, because the roads in East Anglia are almost traffic-free compared
with those of the overcrowded south-east. With the sun shining, it was just
the place for wind in the hair motoring.
The SL stands for superlicht (super-light) although, over many years, these
cars always have struck me as anything but. At close to two tons ready for
the road, the latest 320SL is a fairly massive piece of machinery; almost a
battle tank designer's idea of a sports car.
But its carved-from-solid integrity makes it the strongest, stiffest and
safest open car in the world. It even has a rollover bar deployed
automatically in a fraction of a second if a sensor detects that the car is
in danger of overturning.
This really works. When the present SL was launched five years ago in
Portugal, a girl who should not have been at the wheel up-ended one at speed
on a race track. The car looked distinctly second-hand afterwards, but she
and her passenger walked away.
To get an SL into such a predicament, however, calls for bad luck or inept
driving. Although it rides like a town carriage, its wide track and
sophisticated suspension give it levels of handling and road-holding so high
that they simply cannot be explored on the highway.
The SL has always been the choice of affluent motoring connoisseurs and
their ladies. Many of the owners are no longer young; indeed, it is the kind
of car to which a man might turn naturally on feeling he had grown too old
for a Porsche 911.
Although a cabriolet version of the gull-wing appeared in 1960, I reckon the
latest blood line began with the 'pagoda top' 300SL of 1963 - the one with a
slightly concave roof. Its replacement in 1971 stayed in production until
the present car appeared 18 years later, in 1989.
Since then, more than 106,000 have been made, more than half with
five-litre, V8 engines. Mercedes-Benz murmurs that this is because 'our
customers have a liking for power'. Britons, undaunted by the recession,
have bought more than 5,000 of them and sales now are even more buoyant.
SLs come with in-line, six-cylinder engines of 2.8 and 3.2 litres; the
five-litre V8; or a six-litre V12 at prices ranging from Pounds 53,594 to
Pounds 96,794. All have automatic transmission.
Orders are being taken for a very limited 'hot' edition with a bored-out
six-litre V8, special AMG suspension and ultra-wide wheels. It will cost
between Pounds 85,000 and Pounds 90,000.
I doubt I would like driving that one as much as I did the 320SL. This has a
silk-smooth six-cylinder (231 horsepower at 5,800rpm) which, I thought, gave
it more than enough performance. Foot down hard, the 308hp 500SL I tried
later was more rocket-like, but the extra weight up front made it handle
less sensitively.
All SLs have a power-operated hood and a hard top which you keep in the
garage until winter sets in. The soft top is a masterpiece. It disappears
completely when folded and is the only one I know that is totally automatic,
even to the operation of the clamps that fasten it.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3711 Motor Vehicles and Car Bodies.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Products &amp; Product use.
</TP>
